Novak
initial statement:
 1132
Your Honor, 
I stand before you today to plead guilty to the charge of assault. I admit that I pushed my employee to the ground and kicked him in the stomach. The incident occurred when my employee made a grave mistake at work, which I knew would result in significant financial consequences for my company. The frustration and anger that consumed me in that moment led to this regrettable act. 

Although I acknowledge the severity of my actions, I want to emphasize that I took immediate responsibility for my behavior. As soon as I realized the harm I had caused, I rushed my employee to the closest emergency room to ensure his well-being. I deeply regret my actions and I would like to express my sincerest apologies to the victim and his family for the pain I have caused them. 

In an effort to make amends, I have already taken steps to provide compensation for the victim's medical expenses by offering to pay for the remainder of his hospital bills. I understand that this gesture cannot undo the harm done, but I hope it demonstrates my genuine remorse and willingness to take responsibility for my actions.

Furthermore, I would like to bring to your attention that I am a first-time offender with no prior criminal record. I have always strived to live my life in accordance with the law, and this incident is an aberration in an otherwise law-abiding life.

I also believe it is important to mention that I am 40 years old. While age alone does not excuse my behavior, it may be considered as a mitigating factor since it falls outside the interval where one would expect impulsive actions or poor judgment to be more common.

I understand the seriousness of the offense and the impact it has had on all parties involved. I assure you, Your Honor, that this incident has served as a wake-up call for me. I vow to learn from this experience and take the necessary steps to ensure that such a lapse of judgment never occurs again. 

I respectfully submit to the court that my guilty plea itself is a mitigating factor. By acknowledging my wrongdoing and taking full responsibility for my actions, I hope to show that I am committed to making amends and to prevent such incidents from happening in the future.

In conclusion, I firmly believe that I am not defined solely by this one moment of anger. I have already begun the process of making restitution and have shown remorse for my actions. I humbly request that the court considers these mitigating factors when determining an appropriate sentence.
